<segment id="1" parent="1001" relname="preparation">Get Along With Conceptual</segment>
<segment id="2" parent="1002" relname="preparation">Thinkers</segment>
<segment id="3" parent="1003" relname="span">Ever dealt with someone</segment>
<segment id="4" parent="3" relname="elaboration">who cannot put anything in concrete terms ?</segment>
<segment id="5" parent="1007" relname="span">Someone</segment>
<segment id="6" parent="5" relname="elaboration">who speaks big words</segment>
<segment id="7" parent="1006" relname="joint">and has a broad image of how the world works ,</segment>
<segment id="8" parent="9" relname="condition">but whenever you try to get specifics out of them ,</segment>
<segment id="9" parent="1008" relname="span">it &apos;s like herding cats ?</segment>
<segment id="10" parent="1010" relname="preparation">Steps</segment>
<segment id="11" parent="1012" relname="preparation">Take stock of the individual &apos;s relevance / importance for your everyday life .</segment>
<segment id="12" parent="1013" relname="span">The more important the person is the more you should make an effort</segment>
<segment id="13" parent="1014" relname="span">to relate to them</segment>
<segment id="14" parent="13" relname="elaboration">( and them to you ) .</segment>
<segment id="15" parent="1016" relname="preparation">Explain things on their terms .</segment>
<segment id="16" parent="1017" relname="preparation">For example , is it important to convey to your dad what your college major classes are about ?</segment>
<segment id="17" parent="1019" relname="span">If this matters to you think about &quot; transferable skills &quot; and important lessons</segment>
<segment id="18" parent="17" relname="elaboration">you learn -</segment>
<segment id="19" parent="1020" relname="span">your dad may not care to know about the second derivative problem</segment>
<segment id="20" parent="1021" relname="span">you failed on the exam</segment>
<segment id="21" parent="20" relname="condition">if he &apos;s a conceptual thinker and not a math-whiz .</segment>
<segment id="22" parent="1023" relname="span">Do you need to explain to your roommate</segment>
<segment id="23" parent="22" relname="elaboration">why you need to be alone on Friday night in the apartment ?</segment>
<segment id="24" parent="1026" relname="condition">If he or she is a conceptual thinker</segment>
<segment id="25" parent="1027" relname="span">they will be confused by all your literal</segment>
<segment id="26" parent="25" relname="elaboration">( and detailed )</segment>
<segment id="27" parent="1026" relname="same_unit">Friday evening plans .</segment>
<segment id="28" parent="1029" relname="same_unit">Hearing concepts such as &quot; privacy &quot; , &quot; personal space &quot; , &quot; date &quot; , &quot; movie night &quot;</segment>
<segment id="29" parent="1030" relname="span">may be more important to them than the details of who your date is or what movie</segment>
<segment id="30" parent="29" relname="elaboration">you are planning to see .</segment>
<segment id="31" parent="32" relname="condition">If you are planning to do something with them ,</segment>
<segment id="32" parent="1032" relname="span">patiently and respectfully of your thinking styles try to get them to commit to concrete steps or specifics about what will you do .</segment>
<segment id="33" parent="1034" relname="preparation">For example ,</segment>
<segment id="34" parent="1035" relname="condition">if your friend talks about &quot; big life change &quot; plans ,</segment>
<segment id="35" parent="1036" relname="preparation">get her or him to commit to running once a week with you ,</segment>
<segment id="36" parent="1037" relname="contrast">start an online dating profile ,</segment>
<segment id="37" parent="1038" relname="joint">or pick up the call</segment>
<segment id="38" parent="1038" relname="joint">and inquire about open position about her or his dream job .</segment>
<segment id="39" parent="1040" relname="span">Conceptual thinkers sometimes have a hard time</segment>
<segment id="40" parent="1041" relname="span">making their plans concrete</segment>
<segment id="41" parent="40" relname="cause">because they need to think about details .</segment>
<segment id="42" parent="1043" relname="span">Help them</segment>
<segment id="43" parent="42" relname="elaboration">( and they can help you think in conceptual terms about your business idea , or your career/ life plans ) .</segment>
<segment id="44" parent="1045" relname="preparation">Tips</segment>
<segment id="45" parent="1046" relname="span">Conceptual and literal thinkers may have a hard time</segment>
<segment id="46" parent="1047" relname="contrast">getting along</segment>
<segment id="47" parent="1048" relname="span">but , with the right communication skills and patience ,</segment>
<segment id="48" parent="47" relname="elaboration">they can be wonderful life or work partners .</segment>
<segment id="49" parent="1050" relname="preparation">Think for example of CEO-COO teams :</segment>
<segment id="50" parent="1050" relname="joint">the CEO is in change of vision , mission , inspiring people ;</segment>
<segment id="51" parent="1050" relname="joint">the COO spends time on the nitty-gritty of everyday life .</segment>
<segment id="52" parent="1050" relname="joint">Both are important ,</segment>
<segment id="53" parent="1054" relname="span">and the two have to work together as a team :</segment>
<segment id="54" parent="1055" relname="joint">mission without good execution is bad ,</segment>
<segment id="55" parent="1055" relname="joint">and so is execution without good , clear mission .</segment>
<segment id="56" parent="1050" relname="joint">Check out How to Get Along With Literal Thinkers .</segment>
<segment id="57" parent="1057" relname="span">You may be one of them</segment>
<segment id="58" parent="57" relname="elaboration">in which case conceptual thinkers will make you very uncomfortable with their high-level ideas .</segment>
<segment id="59" parent="1058" relname="span">Warnings</segment>
<segment id="60" parent="1060" relname="span">Working with someone of an opposite thinking type can be both a blessing and a curse</segment>
<segment id="61" parent="60" relname="elaboration">( and sometimes both at the same time ) .</segment>
<segment id="62" parent="1059" relname="joint">Learn to recognize and use each other &apos;s strengths .</segment>
